The parameter is the type-specific reproduction number from a 2x2 next generation matrix. Cases were classified as those who visited multiple healthcare facilities vs others. Case definition is all lab-confirmed cases recorded in this outbreak. The source of infection was available for 169 out of 185 reported cases, the likely infector was inferred based on timing of symptom onset for all but 3 cases (including the index case), and this analysis is based on the resulting network of 182 case pairs. Note that the upper value of R0 is high, but this applies only the the minority of cases that visited multiple healthcare facilities. The overall R0 of the outbreak is reported as 1.0 in the abstract (this is a somewhat trivial result as it is a closed outbreak which gives an R0 =1-1/N).

The parameter is the type-specific reproduction number from a 2x2 next generation matrix. Cases were classified as those who visited multiple healthcare facilities vs others. Case definition is all lab-confirmed cases recorded in this outbreak. The source of infection was available for 169 out of 185 reported cases, and this analysis is based on these. Note that the  upper value of R0 is high, but this applies only the the minority of cases that visited multiple healthcare facilities. The overall R0 of the outbreak is reported as 1.0 in the abstract (this is a somewhat trivial result as it is a closed outbreak which gives an R0 =1-1/N).

The parameter is the Re of the superspreaders only (5 out of 185 cases were identified as superspreaders that were responsible for the vase majority of transmissions). This does not reflect the overall Rt across the whole population.

parameter_notes: The population was split 2 ways: into those that did or didn't cause secondary transmission, and superspreaders vs non-superspreaders, and the mean delay was given for each of the 2 subgroups, for each split: 4 values in total, and each person contributed to 2 of these. The differences between the groups were not significant for either split, and with this in mind I have extracted this according to the rule of 3.

risk factors for mortality in MERS-confirmed patients (not in general population), it's a prospective study so I am not sure with the survey dates and the dates I put in refer to when those patients were admitted to the hospitals

Old age, low albumin, altered mentality and high pneumonia severity index score at admission were risk factors for mortality. In addition, severe signs of inflammation at initial presentation (at hospital days 1-4), such as high inducible protein-10 (p=0.0013), monocyte chemoattractant protein-1 (p=0.0007) and interleukin 6 (p=0.0007) concentrations, and poor viral control (high viral load at hospital days 5-10, p<0.001) without adequate antibody titres (low antibody titre at hospital days 11-16, p=0.07) during the course of disease, were associated with mortality.
